        "text": "Consult Summary\n53-year-old male presents with a one-week history of left elbow swelling, diagnosed as olecranon bursitis. Plan for blood tests and trial of NSAIDs.\n\nProblem List:\nLeft Elbow Swelling\n- Onset 1/52, noticed in the shower.\n- Described as a weird pain, slightly warm, feels like fluid inside.\n- No history of trauma or injury.\n- No previous episodes.\n- Denies family history of rheumatological disease.\n- Examination (via video):\n- Swelling noted over the left olecranon.\n- Skin appears dry over the tip of the elbow.\n- Reports area is slightly warm to touch.\n- Tender to palpation adjacent to the olecranon tip, but not on the tip itself.\n- Differential diagnosis: Olecranon bursitis, septic arthritis, gout, inflammatory arthritis.\n- Septic arthritis considered unlikely at present.\n\nPast Medical History:\n- Osteoarthritis (diagnosed by GP a few years ago)\n\nAllergies:\n- Peanuts\n- No known drug allergies\n\nSocial History:\n- Works a desk job.\n- Runs regularly 2-3 times per week.\n\nPlan:\n- Commence Ibuprofen 400mg BD PO with food.\n- Blood test form to be sent for inflammatory markers, infection screen, rheumatological antibodies, and gout screen.\n- Safety-netted to seek urgent review if elbow becomes very red, very painful, or if redness spreads.\n- Follow-up appointment (phone, video, or face-to-face) to be arranged after blood tests are completed to review results."
